      passage: `The following text is from Julia Alvarez&rsquo;s 2000 novel <em>In the Name of Salom&eacute;</em>. Salom&eacute;, a poet, is hosting guests in the front parlor of her family home, and Ramona is her sister. A salon is a social gathering for the exploration of intellectual ideas.<br><br>It was evening when the two men got up to leave. T&iacute;a Ana had already come into the room several times to see if these guests had departed yet. The front parlor had always been her special province, as she used it for her little school. Now, every evening, it turned into Salom&eacute;&rsquo;s salon, as Ramona called it, and it was never in order for its transformation back to a classroom the following morning.`,
